@ulrichard: You definitely have a valid point with which I totally agree. Some authors are already working with the [pay what you want](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pay_what_you_want) model and some just give ebooks for free because they know it may increase sales for physical books.
Antilibrary doesn't want to become a store. What it wants instead is to **give access** to the knowledge contained in books. Unlike what happens with entertainment or music, free ebooks are taken as 'free samples'. That is, people that consume free ebooks is people who would not have purchased the book in first place, but after reading a *pirated* book may end up purchasing a hard copy. If you google about the subject you will see that there's evidence to both outcomes (piracy hurting sales vs piracy increasing sales).
There is much more investment from the part of the reader on a book than on a movie for example. If the book is good the reader will be compelled to read more from that author and probably support the author. It's a deeper connection between creator and consumer.
But you made a good point. I'll make sure I add something to the site saying that supporting authors is probably the most important thing readers can do when they enjoy a book. 


@P2P: no need to run IPFS. The files are downloaded through the public IPFS gateway. All you need to do is to rename the files after the download.

@Jayofthezero: Thanks for reporting both issues.
The first problem is sorted. For some reason the seedbox was restarted (never happened before). I'll do something to avoid that in the future.
The second problem must be due to the quantity of books related to math. This should be solved once I implement pagination on the search results.
